brewery.brewery_description:
Why shouldn’t every area have its own local brewery?

We’re going to be the ones to bring this.

beer.beer_description:
Collab: The Social Brewers × Riverside Brewing

Bold, red, and dangerously smooth — Daytripper takes your tastebuds on a joyride. Brewed with thiolised yeast for an amped-up tropical aroma, this Red IPL drops juicy stone fruit and passionfruit notes on a rich, biscuity malt backbone. Crisp lager finish. Double trouble vibes.

items.badge_description: Get out there and raise a ruckus with your favorite Amber or Red Ale! That's 35 different amber or red beers. Try 5 more for Level 8!

beer.beer_description:
There was one player who would always make the English look dark and mild. Sir Donald Bradman. On 27th November 1926, Bradman took his place in the St George First Grade team at Hurstville Oval. The young cricketer broke his bat on 98 and managed 110 on debut.

Broken Bat is a super drinkable mid-strength with tonnes of flavour, allowing you to bat on. Great for those long sessions at the crease.

items.badge_description: Fresh from the tap is one of the best ways to enjoy a beer. Just try to use a glass and not drink directly from the tap, as tempting as it may be. That's 245 checkins with the serving style of Draft. Try 5 more for Level 50!

beer.beer_description: This one’s for the Barrys of the world — the teachers, the brewers, the legends. Rich, roasty and award-winning, this dark lager’s got more tradition than your aunty’s Christmas pavlova. Pouring deep mahogany with notes of caramel, cocoa and roasted nuts, it’s smooth, smart and keeps it clean. Adapted from Barry’s Best in Show home brew recipe.

items.badge_description: It takes the perfect amount of light, the right framing and a touch of creative love to get the perfect picture of your brew. Now it’s time to drink it! That's 405 check-ins with a photo.  Try 5 more for Level 82!

At first taste, dark ales can be overwhelming for even the most skilled of beer drinkers, but your will is weak and with time you will eventually turn to the dark side. That's 25 different beers with the style of Dark Ale, Belgian Strong Dark Ale, Lager - Dark, IPA - Black / Cascadian Dark Ale or IPA - Imperial / Double Black, Schwarzbier, or Mild - Dark. Try 5 more for Level 6!

beer.beer_description:
In typical Australian fashion, Forest Road was named after the forest it ran through, by the convicts who built it.

Forest Road IPA combines the malt backbone of an English IPA with American hops to create a forest of earthy, piney aromas as well as citrus and stone fruit. Smooth as freshly laid bitumen.

This one’s for the Barrys of the world — the teachers, the brewers, the legends. Rich, roasty and award-winning, this dark lager’s got more tradition than your aunty’s Christmas pavlova. Pouring deep mahogany with notes of caramel, cocoa and roasted nuts, it’s smooth, smart and keeps it clean. Adapted from Barry’s Best in Show home brew recipe.

beer.beer_description:
Collab: The Social Brewers × Riverside Brewing

Bold, red, and dangerously smooth — Daytripper takes your tastebuds on a joyride. Brewed with thiolised yeast for an amped-up tropical aroma, this Red IPL drops juicy stone fruit and passionfruit notes on a rich, biscuity malt backbone. Crisp lager finish. Double trouble vibes.

In typical Australian fashion, Forest Road was named after the forest it ran through, by the convicts who built it.

Forest Road IPA combines the malt backbone of an English IPA with American hops to create a forest of earthy, piney aromas as well as citrus and stone fruit. Smooth as freshly laid bitumen.

Long celebrated as an idyllic spot for day trips and holiday makers, Sans Souci (‘no worries’ in French), is a place of respite nestled on the shores of Botany Bay.

Named to reflect the attitude of many who visit, No Worries is the embodiment of rest and relaxation. This is a juicy, hazy beer packed full of tropical fruit aromas. Full bodied with a bitterness that reminds you it’s an IPA at heart.

Striders are a well-known phenomenon around the streets of Peakhurst. Resplendent in orange they're more common in the Summer months, but they've been spotted right throughout the year. Always approachable and refreshing, this fresh Session Ale is designed to be enjoyed and won't slow you down too much. Whether you're enjoying one on your driveway with your neighbour after finishing your daily 'huffy puffy', Striders Session Ale is sure to hit the spot.

Striders Session Ale is an extremely drinkable, dry finishing Ale, with a floral and melon aroma from Galaxy and Enigma hops.

There was one player who would always make the English look dark and mild. Sir Donald Bradman. On 27th November 1926, Bradman took his place in the St George First Grade team at Hurstville Oval. The young cricketer broke his bat on 98 and managed 110 on debut.

Broken Bat is a super drinkable mid-strength with tonnes of flavour, allowing you to bat on. Great for those long sessions at the crease.

An English Porter, Vegemite, Stale Bread, and Indigenous Macadamia Nuts create a harmonic treaty of flavours. Some might prefer division, but we want to show how much better everything, especially beer, can be when we recognise and celebrate Indigenous Australia. A homage to Vegemite Toast.

To celebrate The Social Brewers first trip around the sun, we've brewed an absolute banger of a beer!
Named in honour of our home suburb, Mortdale, or literally translated from Latin 'Valley of the Dead', this Triple Dry-Hopped Double IPA delights the senses with a huge hit of candy, citrus and tropical fruits from over 3kg of Superdelic hops! Only just released as a commercially named hop by @nzhopsltd, it's Superdelic-ious.
To balance the hop flavours and aromas we pumped up the malt bill using 100% @voyager_craft_malt and pushed the mash tun to squeeze out 150L at 8.2% ABV.

GABS2024 Festival Beer - Our standard Dark Mild, named in honour of Don Bradman has been given a dose of Indigenous Ooray (Davidson) Plum. Just like The Don himself when he was knocked over by Indigenous cricketer Eddie Gilbert on November 6, 1931. Dubbed by Bradman as The Fastest Bowler he'd ever seen, Gilbert took Sir Donald and gave him what for - much like we've done by whacking a stack of Ooray Plum in a traditional English Dark Mild..

If you squint you might see a glacier. From the shores of Georges River in Edith Bay, to the mountainous climb up to Chivers Hill, 'Luggas' is Sydney's piece of Europe - home to one notorious, unreliable punt...

Once the only way to cross the river, the Lugarno Ferry made it's final journey on December 12, 1974, after many years of sometimes dodgy service.

Named after a suburb named after a place in Switzerland, LagerNo is a refreshing, malty melody balanced with subtle yeast characteristics. Not really a lager but designed for lager lovers.

Celebrating women in the brewing industry, this beer is designed to show off the 2022 Pink Boots hop blend from Yakima Chief Hops. With hop additions at 60, 30 and 15 minutes as well as in the whirlpool and a generous dry-hop we wanted to show everything we could about this great blend. Layers of floral notes combine with citrus, stone fruits and wood.

Our winter seasonal is inspired by the timber cutters and lumber mills which once covered the area.

Oat-ley is a smooth, rich and full-bodied stout brewed with lashings of oats and a hint of smokiness. Roast malts give this beer chocolate and coffee flavours and it's easy to get lost in the darkness.
A traditionally styled South-German Hefeweizen. The yeast character and gentle touch of Curtis floats on a cloud of wheat haze. Der Grosvater of hazy beers.

Sometimes you just need to get away, and nothing says "relaxation" like swinging past Hunts Marine for a new bung and firing up the Evinrude. 

When you're the Captain, you choose your destination... right?

Hunts Holiday Hazy Pale Ale has a generous hit of passionfruit aroma and flavour from the NZ hop combo of Riwaka and Moutere and plenty of malt backbone to carry it through.
Like the brackish waters of Salt Pan Creek this beer is slightly salty. Sour with a crisp finish and a touch of coriander. A great summer beer.

Whether it's St George, Boy George or King George, every George you can name has done things a little differently. Our autumn seasonal beer is no exception.

Similar in colour to the river that shares its name, but with a few less bull sharks, Georges is a malty and moorish American Amber Ale with hints of caramel and a gentle touch of green apple.

Akasha Collab!

Can you make a Hazy IPA with no dry hop?? WWE teamed up with our mates down the M8 to find out. 

Brewed using Maui Nelson hop kief, Abstrax King Louie terpenes and Neumaker New E yeast with Fermoplus Fruity & Fermoplus Sauvignon to promote hop thiolisation.

Much like our own little slice of LaLa Land, Beverly Hills West Coast IPA takes a traditional American classic and tones it down so you can enjoy it over and over again.

Made with classic American hops plus a dash of something different to give it a Southern Hemisphere touch.

Limited release brewed in partnership with local football club, Penshurst West.

A tasty American Pale Ale using Sabro hops, supported by a malt bill of Voyager Compass, Munich and SM40. At 33.5 IBU, it’s medium bitterness, and it has a great colour.

Brewed on the boundary — where Aotearoa’s citrusy Wai-iti hops meet Mortdale’s laid-back local flavour.

Crisp, clean, and quietly confident, Paenga Pilsner carries floral notes, gentle bitterness, and a nod to the Māori word for “edge.”

XX ESB – A Toast to 20 Years of Brewing Excellence!

Brewed in collaboration with the legendary Extra Special Brewers brew club, to celebrate two decades of homebrew mastery, XX ESB is a true labour of love. Adapted from an award-winning recipe by one of their finest, this limited-release brew features the finest Voyager Craft Malt, classic Bluestone Yeast Yorkshire Yeast, and hops generously donated by The Brew Shop AU.

Rich, balanced, and full of character, it’s a pint crafted to honour the passion and craft of homebrewers everywhere. Cheers to 20 years!
This sour combines a little lactose, pineapple, lime juice with a touch of sourness.

The first beer brewed by our own Big Red, Celia under the careful stewardship of Head Brewer, Beau.
Beautifully crafted with just the right amount of bitterness from English hops and delightful sweetness from locally sourced malt.
We took a regular German Lager and turned up the volume. Big can. Big flavour. Big fun!
In honour of two great local brewers, we've recreated Marist Märzen. Based on a closely guarded recipe with rich biscuit and bready aromas with balanced bitterness.
